"{\"uid\": \"eastidahonews.com-2024-08-rexburgs-hawkins-falters-in-high-jump-following-strong-olympic-start\", \"text\": \"Mon  29  51    Mon  67  63    Nov 25  47  30    Nov 25  55  61    Nov 25  29  65    Nov 25  72  56    Nov 25  42  34    Nov 25  27  28    Idaho Falls news, Rexburg news, Pocatello news, East Idaho news, Idaho news, education news, crime news, good news, business news, entertainment news, Feel Good Friday and more.  SAINT-DENIS, France - Local Olympian Chari Hawkins failed on her three attempts at clearing 1.71 meters in the high jump, dropping her from fifth to 22nd place on Thursday.  Hawkins began her Paris Olympics appearance with a strong showing in the 100-meter hurdles, finishing in 13.16 seconds to earn 1,100 points. After heading into the second of seven events in fifth place, she failed to clear her initial height in the high jump and received zero points, effectively removing her from any medal contention.  The Rexburg native was just 44 points behind the leader, Annik Kaelin of Switzerland, following the hurdles. Her personal best in the high jump is 1.85 meters.  RELATED | Rexburg woman continues quest for Olympic gold Thursday morning - with her family in attendance  Fellow Americans Taliyah Brooks and Anna Hall entered the second event Thursday morning in second and sixth place, respectively.  Brooks cleared her first three heights, but failed three times at 1.8 meters and finished the event with 941 points. Hall cleared a seven jumps finishing third in the event with a jump of 1.89 meters to earn 1,093 points.  Through the first two events of the competition, both Hall (third place with 2,164 points) and Brooks (sixth place with 2,065 points) remain in medal contention. Katarina Johnson-Thompson, of Great Britain, is the leader at the mid-day break with 2,197 points.  Hawkins' 1,100 points are ahead of only Germany's Sophie Weissenberg, who was injured during warmups of the hurdles and has yet to compete.  Hawkins, Hall, Brooks and the women of the heptathlon will return to Stade de France at 11:30 a.m. (MT) for the shot put then 200-meter race. The competition will conclude Friday afternoon.  SUBMIT A CORRECTION  We hope you appreciated this story.\\u00a0  \\t\\tA small team of local journalists runs EastIdahoNews.com - not a big business or corporation. Our stories are produced to inform and serve the public. We do not have a paywall or require a subscription to use EastIdahoNews.com, but there is a cost associated with bringing you stories every day. Please consider supporting us just once for $1 or, if you are able, contribute a little more monthly or annually. We sincerely appreciate your consideration.  Donation amount:$      \\u00a9 2015 - 2025 EastIdahoNews.com\\u00a0LLC\"}"